Global Disparities in Hib Vaccine Coverage & Healthcare Access

Author

Lakshmi Priya

Published

April 26, 2024

Introduction

Immunization is one of the most effective ways to protect children from life-threatening diseases. This dashboard focuses on the Percentage of surviving infants who received the third dose of Hib-containing vaccine, a critical measure of global healthcare accessibility and effectiveness. The Hib vaccine protects against Haemophilus influenzae type B, a leading cause of bacterial meningitis and pneumonia in young children. High vaccination coverage ensures stronger immunity, reducing child mortality rates significantly.

Code 
import polars as pl

schema = {"Total population": pl.Float64}
df = pl.read_csv("Hib.csv", schema_overrides=schema)
pdf = df.to_pandas()
Code 
import geopandas as gpd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

shape_world = gpd.read_file("https://public.opendatasoft.com/api/explore/v2.1/catalog/datasets/world-administrative-boundaries/exports/shp")
pdf = pdf.rename(columns={"Country": "name"})

map_data = shape_world.merge(pdf, on="name", how="left")

fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 1, figsize=(15, 10))

map_data.plot(
    column='Obs Value (%)',
    cmap='YlGnBu',
    legend=True,
    ax=ax,
    missing_kwds={"color": "pink"},
    edgecolor="black",
    legend_kwds={"label": "Immunization Rate (%)", "shrink": 0.6}
)

ax.set_title('Global Hib Immunization Coverage', fontsize=20, fontweight='bold')
ax.set_axis_off()
plt.show()

  • High Coverage: Most countries in Europe, parts of Asia (such as Japan and South Korea), Australia, and several South American nations show very high immunization rates (above 80%), reflected by the deep blue tones.

  • Moderate Coverage: Some countries in Africa, Southeast Asia, and Central America display moderate immunization rates (40â70%), shown in lighter blue shades.

  • Low Coverage: Areas highlighted in pink, such as parts of North America, South America, Africa, and Asia, indicate countries with lower immunization rates (below 40%). These countries may face challenges such as limited healthcare access, vaccine hesitancy, or logistical issues in vaccine distribution.

Code 
from plotnine import *

(
    ggplot(data=df)
    + aes(x="GDP per capita ($)", y="Hospital beds (per 1,000 people)", color="Continent")
    + geom_point(alpha=0.6, size=2)
    + geom_smooth(method="lm", se=False, color="black")
    + scale_color_brewer(type='qual', palette='Set2')
    + labs(
        title="Relationship between GDP per Capita and Hospital Beds Availability",
        x="GDP per capita ($)",
        y="Hospital beds (per 1,000 people)"
    )
    + theme_minimal()
    + theme(
        plot_title=element_text(size=10, weight="bold")
    )
)

The trend line shows a negative correlation; wealthier countries tend to have fewer hospital beds per 1,000 people. This could be due to advanced outpatient care, shorter hospital stays, and improved healthcare efficiency. In contrast, lower-income nations often have more hospital beds, possibly due to higher demand for inpatient care and different healthcare infrastructure.

(

        x="GDP per capita ($)",
        y="Life Expectancy at Birth (years)"
    )
    + theme_minimal()
    + theme(
        plot_title=element_text(size=10, weight="bold")
    )
)

The trend line shows a strong correlation between GDP per capita and life expectancy. Wealthier nations tend to have longer life spans due to better healthcare and living conditions. Lower-income countries, clustered at the bottom left, face healthcare challenges, leading to shorter life expectancy. This highlights the impact of economic development on public health.

Code 
df_avg = (
    pdf.groupby(["Year", "Continent"])["Obs Value (%)"]
    .mean()
    .reset_index()
)
(
    ggplot(data=df_avg)
    + aes(x="Year", y="Obs Value (%)", color="Continent")
    + geom_line(size=1)
    + geom_point(size=1)
    + scale_color_brewer(type='qual', palette='Set2')
    + scale_x_continuous(breaks=[2003, 2008, 2013, 2018, 2023])
    + labs(
        title="Global Progress in Immunization Rates",
        x="Year",
        y="Average Hib Immunization Rate (%)",
        color="Continent"
    )
    + theme_minimal()
    + theme(
        plot_title=element_text(size=10, weight="bold")
    )
)

The chart shows the trend of average immunization rates (%) across different continents from 2003 to 2023. Overall, Europe and North America maintained high immunization rates above 90%, while Africa consistently had the lowest rates.A sharp dip is noticeable in Africa around 2004, after which the rates gradually improved but remained lower compared to other continents. Fluctuations are observed in Asia and Australia, indicating variability in immunization programs over the years.

Code 
(
    ggplot(pdf)
    + aes(x="Continent", y="Life expectancy at birth (years)", fill="Continent")
    + geom_boxplot()
    + scale_fill_brewer(type='qual', palette='Set2')
    + labs(
        title="Distribution of Life Expectancy at Birth by Continent",
        x="Continent",
        y="Life expectancy at birth (years)"
    )
    + theme_minimal()
    + theme(
        plot_title=element_text(size=10, weight="bold")
    )
)

Europe and Australia show the highest median life expectancy, with most values concentrated between 75 and 85 years. Africa has the lowest median life expectancy and also shows a wider spread, indicating greater variation across countries. Asia, North America, and South America have similar ranges, with life expectancy typically between 70 and 80 years. Overall, the chart highlights regional disparities in health outcomes globally.

Code 
(
    ggplot(pdf)
    + aes(x="Year", y="GDP per capita ($)", fill="Continent")
    + geom_col(position=position_dodge(width=0.8))
    + scale_x_continuous(breaks=[2003, 2008, 2013, 2018, 2023])
    + scale_fill_brewer(type='qual', palette='Set2')
    + labs(
        title="GDP per Capita Trends by Continent (2003â2023)",
        x="Year",
        y="GDP per capita ($)",
        fill="Continent"
    )
    + theme_minimal()
    + theme(
        plot_title=element_text(size=10, weight="bold")
    )
)

This chart shows the growth in GDP per capita across continents from 2003 to 2023. Europe contributes the largest share to global GDP per capita over the years, followed by Asia and North America. All continents show a general upward trend, although the growth rate slightly fluctuates around 2009â2010, likely due to the global financial crisis. Africa and South America contribute smaller portions but also display steady growth over time. The chart highlights how economic growth has been distributed differently across regions, with Europe and Asia showing significant increases.

Code 
(
    ggplot(pdf)
    + aes(x="Year", y="Life expectancy at birth (years)", color="Continent")
    + geom_point(alpha=0.2, size=1)
    + geom_smooth(method="lm")
    + facet_wrap("Continent", ncol=3)
    + scale_x_continuous(breaks=[2003, 2008, 2013])
    + labs(
        x="Year (from 2003 to 2023)",
        y="Life expectancy at birth (years)",
        title="Life Expectancy Trends per Continent"
    )
    + theme_minimal()
    + theme(
        plot_title=element_text(size=10, weight="bold")
    )
)

Europe and Australia show the highest life expectancy. Africa shows the lowest median life expectancy and a wider spread, highlighting disparities.

Conclusion

This dashboard highlights the global disparities in healthcare and economic development.

Wealthier nations tend to have higher life expectancy, fewer hospital beds per capita, and better immunization rates, while lower-income regions struggle with healthcare infrastructure and vaccine distribution.

The gap between Africa and Europe is evident in GDP, hospital access, and immunization rates, emphasizing the need for stronger healthcare investments in developing regions.

Expanding vaccination programs and improving healthcare accessibility are crucial steps to reducing these inequalities and ensuring a healthier future for all children worldwide.
